# Stream 2 — AI Toxicity Prediction Models

This folder contains the deep learning models for toxicity prediction.

## Approach

Two complementary self-supervised approaches are explored:

**Semi-supervised learning** — learns from large amounts of unlabelled molecular data, then fine-tunes on labelled toxicity data.

**Contrastive learning** — learns meaningful molecular representations by contrasting similar and dissimilar compounds, then fine-tunes on labelled data.

Both models are multi-modal: they learn from chemical structures (SMILES) and biological assay data.

## Current results

- 76% accuracy on test data (preliminary)
- Scaffold-based splitting used to prevent data leakage
- Further optimisation in progress

## Folder structure

```
model/
├── pretraining/
│   ├── semi_supervised.py    # Self-supervised pretraining
│   └── contrastive.py        # Contrastive pretraining
├── finetuning/
│   └── finetune.py           # Fine-tune on labelled toxicity endpoints
├── evaluation/
│   ├── scaffold_split.py     # Scaffold-based train/test split
│   └── metrics.py            # Accuracy, AUC, per-endpoint results
├── checkpoints/              # Saved model weights (not committed to git)
└── api/
    └── serve.py              # FastAPI endpoint — serves predictions to frontend
```

## Running the model

```bash
pip install -r requirements.txt

# Pretrain
python pretraining/semi_supervised.py

# Fine-tune
python finetuning/finetune.py

# Serve predictions to frontend
python api/serve.py
```

## API output format

The `serve.py` endpoint returns predictions in the `ProToxPrediction` format defined in `docs/schema.md`. This ensures the frontend can swap between ProTox-II and our model without any code changes.

```json
{
  "smiles": "...",
  "ld50": 200,
  "toxicity_class": 3,
  "toxicity_class_label": "Toxic",
  "endpoints": {
    "hepatotoxicity": true,
    "nephrotoxicity": false
  }
}
```
